      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hi, I'm studying for my intro to econ exam and I'm a bit stuck on the concept of opportunity cost. Could you give me a real-world example of it? Like, maybe a company deciding between two different things, like buying new equipment or spending more on marketing? Thanks!",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's imagine a company named \"Gadget Galore\" that has a choice to either buy new equipment or invest in more marketing. If they choose to buy new equipment, the opportunity cost is the potential increase in sales that could have been achieved through additional marketing. On the other hand, if they decide to spend more on marketing, the opportunity cost would be the potential efficiency gains and productivity that could have been gained from the new equipment. In other words, the company must weigh the benefits of each option and decide which one will ultimately lead to greater gains for their business.",
